eeds small business.</p></div><p>America is getting older.</p><p>Not in the sense the country will have its 237th birthday this July 4. Rather, the population is aging at a rate not seen before.</p><p>Chalk it up to the end of World War II. Baby boomers, those born between 1946 and 1964, constitute a major percentage of the U.S. population. Those born in the early stages of the movement turned 65, a common retirement age, in 2011.</p><p>The aging population presents some complications – a talent gap in the workforce as boomers head for retirement – but also a number of opportunities for entrepreneurs with ideas for starting a small business that serves the needs of seniors.</p><p><a href=\"http://income.com/\">Income.com</a> has always believed in deferring to our elders, but now it may be time to make some money while having to sit through grandpa’s umpteenth telling of that time him and Jimmy from the block sold newspapers for a nickel - A nickel!</p><p>There’s a number of options to go with when trying to think of <a href=\"http://www.sba.gov/community/blogs/community-blogs/small-business-cents/starting-senior-care-business\" target=\"_blank\">ideas for starting a small business that caters to senior</a> living and care demands. Retirement communities and care services aren’t the only possibility. Can’t remember the last time you set down your smartphone? Seminars on technology training are a hot ticket. Got a lead – but still steady – foot? Senior transport services may be your calling.</p><p>There’s more to small businesses designed to serve senior citizens than tapioca pudding and re-runs of the Lawrence Welk show, and entrepreneurs should <a href=\"http://smallbusiness.chron.com/start-nonmedical-senior-home-care-business-not-franchise-opportunity-14278.html\" target=\"_blank\">investigate startups in the industry</a> if they want to take advantage of a booming trend.</p><h2><strong>Transportation Services</strong></h2><p>Seniors with prescription lenses as thick as the phonebook aren’t exactly the most suitable drivers on the road. That makes getting around a hassle for many that need to get to doctor appointments, general shopping and meetups with friends. Further exacerbating the situation is the fact family members often live separately and don’t have the time outside of work and other life responsibilities to help. Public transportation, while offering senior discounts, is also out of the question for many.</p><p>Here’s where you can come in with a new set of wheels. Seniors need reliable transportation services, and a comforting one at that. Such a business would entail you, or drivers you hire, chauffeuring seniors around, waiting for them when running errands or while they go to a medical visit. Make sure you have at least one vehicle that accommodates wheelchair users with lifts and extra seat spacing.</p><h2><strong>Traveling Tech Wizard</strong></h2><p>Now that their grandchildren, and most likely their children themselves, are on the frontline of the technology age, seniors need to learn basics of online communication and tasks in case they want to keep in touch with family and friends in a more convenient way than soup cans and string.</p><p>You can start by publicizing yourself to retirement care facilities around your area and pitching a tech training seminar. If all goes well, they’ll call back for more so other residents get the chance to check out this newfangled contraption they call “the interweb.”</p><p>Some topics you can go over is simple word processor applications like Microsoft Word, the fundamentals to sending, reading and receiving emails, face time, and the <a href=\"http://income.com/90/social-media-a-proven-marketing-initiative-for-entrepreneurs/\" target=\"_blank\">basics of social media</a>for those brave souls who dare venture to wade into the Facebook fray.</p><p><a href=\"http://income.com/\">Income.com</a> sees a hot market on the horizon for senior living and care businesses. But it’s likely entrepreneurs like you will clog the industry. In that case, you need to set yourself apart from the others who start the same tired retirement living and healthcare firms. Make a name for yourself by providing transport services or tech training; <a href=\"http://income.com/67/3-keys-for-starting-a-successful-small-business/\" target=\"_blank\">in addition to the money you’ll make</a>, you might even get a butterscotch candy out of it.</p><p><a href=\"http://income.com/forum/forum.php\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" title=\"ebook-banner\" alt=\" \" src=\"http://income.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/Community_banner.png\" width=\"468\" height=\"60\" /></a></p><p style=\"text-align: center\"><a href=\"http://www.mylanderpages.com/income/howtocreateawebsiteebook_4\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-577\" title=\"ebook-banner\" alt=\" \" src=\"http://income.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/howtocreateawebsiteebook1.png\" width=\"641\" height=\"123\" /></a></p><p>The post <a href=\"http://income.com/1937/senior-living-and-care-2-ideas-for-starting-a-small-business/\">Senior Living And Care: 2 Ideas For Starting A Small Business</a> appeared first on <a href=\"http://income.com\">income.com</a>.</p><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/income/YOKa/~4/6iH5-hPObjo\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\"/>" "http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/income/YOKa/~3/6iH5-hPObjo/" (20811 6614) new 2 nil nil ((title nil "Senior Living And Care: 2 Ideas For Starting A Small Business") (link nil "http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/income/YOKa/~3/6iH5-hPObjo/") (comments nil "http://income.com/1937/senior-living-and-care-2-ideas-for-starting-a-small-business/#comments") (pubDate nil "Thu, 21 Mar 2013 14:31:50 +0000") (dc:creator nil "Tedd Johnson") (category nil "Articles") (category nil "Ideas For Starting A Small Business") (category nil "Small Business") (guid ((isPermaLink . "false")) "http://income.com/?p=1937") (description nil "<p>America is getting older. Not in the sense the country will have its 237th birthday this July 4. Rather, the population is aging at a rate not seen before. Chalk it up to the end of World War II. Baby boomers, those born between 1946 and 1964, constitute a major percentage of the U.S. population. [...]</p><p>The post <a href=\"http://income.com/1937/senior-living-and-care-2-ideas-for-starting-a-small-business/\">Senior Living And Care: 2 Ideas For Starting A Small Business</a> appeared first on <a href=\"http://income.com\">income.com</a>.</p>") (content:encoded nil "<div id=\"attachment_1938\" class=\"wp-caption alignleft\" style=\"width: 310px\"><a href=\"http://income.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/x_0_0_0_14083710_300.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-1938\" alt=\"The population is aging, and you can capitalize on it by starting a senior needs small business.\" src=\"http://income.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/x_0_0_0_14083710_300.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" /></a><p class=\"wp-caption-text\">The population is aging, and you can capitalize on it by starting a senior needs small business.</p></div><p>America is getting older.</p><p>Not in the sense the country will have its 237th birthday this July 4. Rather, the population is aging at a rate not seen before.</p><p>Chalk it up to the end of World War II. Baby boomers, those born between 1946 and 1964, constitute a major percentage of the U.S. population. Those born in the early stages of the movement turned 65, a common retirement age, in 2011.</p><p>The aging population presents some complications &#8211; a talent gap in the workforce as boomers head for retirement &#8211; but also a number of opportunities for entrepreneurs with ideas for starting a small business that serves the needs of seniors.</p><p><a href=\"http://income.com/\">Income.com</a> has always believed in deferring to our elders, but now it may be time to make some money while having to sit through grandpa&#8217;s umpteenth telling of that time him and Jimmy from the block sold newspapers for a nickel - A nickel!</p><p>There&#8217;s a number of options to go with when trying to think of <a href=\"http://www.sba.gov/community/blogs/community-blogs/small-business-cents/starting-senior-care-business\" target=\"_blank\">ideas for starting a small business that caters to senior</a> living and care demands. Retirement communities and care services aren&#8217;t the only possibility. Can&#8217;t remember the last time you set down your smartphone? Seminars on technology training are a hot ticket. Got a lead &#8211; but still steady &#8211; foot? Senior transport services may be your calling.</p><p>There&#8217;s more to small businesses designed to serve senior citizens than tapioca pudding and re-runs of the Lawrence Welk show, and entrepreneurs should <a href=\"http://smallbusiness.chron.com/start-nonmedical-senior-home-care-business-not-franchise-opportunity-14278.html\" target=\"_blank\">investigate startups in the industry</a> if they want to take advantage of a booming trend.</p><h2><strong>Transportation Services</strong></h2><p>Seniors with prescription lenses as thick as the phonebook aren&#8217;t exactly the most suitable drivers on the road. That makes getting around a hassle for many that need to get to doctor appointments, general shopping and meetups with friends. Further exacerbating the situation is the fact family members often live separately and don&#8217;t have the time outside of work and other life responsibilities to help. Public transportation, while offering senior discounts, is also out of the question for many.</p><p>Here&#8217;s where you can come in with a new set of wheels. Seniors need reliable transportation services, and a comforting one at that. Such a business would entail you, or drivers you hire, chauffeuring seniors around, waiting for them when running errands or while they go to a medical visit. Make sure you have at least one vehicle that accommodates wheelchair users with lifts and extra seat spacing.</p><h2><strong>Traveling Tech Wizard</strong></h2><p>Now that their grandchildren, and most likely their children themselves, are on the frontline of the technology age, seniors need to learn basics of online communication and tasks in case they want to keep in touch with family and friends in a more convenient way than soup cans and string.</p><p>You can start by publicizing yourself to retirement care facilities around your area and pitching a tech training seminar. If all goes well, they&#8217;ll call back for more so other residents get the chance to check out this newfangled contraption they call &#8220;the interweb.&#8221;</p><p>Some topics you can go over is simple word processor applications like Microsoft Word, the fundamentals to sending, reading and receiving emails, face time, and the <a href=\"http://income.com/90/social-media-a-proven-marketing-initiative-for-entrepreneurs/\" target=\"_blank\">basics of social media</a>for those brave souls who dare venture to wade into the Facebook fray.</p><p><a href=\"http://income.com/\">Income.com</a> sees a hot market on the horizon for senior living and care businesses. But it&#8217;s likely entrepreneurs like you will clog the industry. In that case, you need to set yourself apart from the others who start the same tired retirement living and healthcare firms. Make a name for yourself by providing transport services or tech training; <a href=\"http://income.com/67/3-keys-for-starting-a-successful-small-business/\" target=\"_blank\">in addition to the money you&#8217;ll make</a>, you might even get a butterscotch candy out of it.</p><p><a href=\"http://income.com/forum/forum.php\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" title=\"ebook-banner\" alt=\" \" src=\"http://income.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/Community_banner.png\" width=\"468\" height=\"60\" /></a></p><p style=\"text-align: center\"><a href=\"http://www.mylanderpages.com/income/howtocreateawebsiteebook_4\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-577\" title=\"ebook-banner\" alt=\" \" src=\"http://income.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/howtocreateawebsiteebook1.png\" width=\"641\" height=\"123\" /></a></p><p>The post <a href=\"http://income.com/1937/senior-living-and-care-2-ideas-for-starting-a-small-business/\">Senior Living And Care: 2 Ideas For Starting A Small Business</a> appeared first on <a href=\"http://income.com\">income.com</a>.</p><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/income/YOKa/~4/6iH5-hPObjo\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\"/>") (wfw:commentRss nil "http://income.com/1937/senior-living-and-care-2-ideas-for-starting-a-small-business/feed/") (slash:comments nil "0") (feedburner:origLink nil "http://income.com/1937/senior-living-and-care-2-ideas-for-starting-a-small-business/"))) ("Grow Your Small Business By Exporting" "<div id=\"attachment_1935\" class=\"wp-caption alignleft\" style=\"width: 310px\"><a href=\"http://income.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/x_0_0_0_14084634_300.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-1935\" alt=\"Ecommerce helps facilitate small-business exporting.  \" src=\"http://income.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/x_0_0_0_14084634_300.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"220\" /></a><p class=\"wp-caption-text\">Ecommerce helps facilitate small-business exporting.</p></div><p>U.S. entrepreneurs benefit immensely from residing in one of the most populous consumer markets: 300 million people is a big number.</p><p>But so too is the some 6.7 billion other individuals that constitute the world’s population outside of the states.</p><p>Want some small-business tips for success? All those people are consumers in their own right, too. If you are serious about making your small business all it can be, you need to investigate exporting if you want to tap the growing global market and establish your startup as a true force to be reckoned with.</p><p>However, <a href=\"http://income.com/\">Income.com</a> understands that many entrepreneurs, while still in tune with a global perspective, don’t have much knowledge on the subject of exports, how the logistics work out and which foreign markets are the best. In order to prime your business for exporting, it may help to consider federal assistance and do a little homework on where your products would sell the best.</p><h2><strong>SBA Can Help</strong></h2><p>While it’s quite clear entrepreneurs like to operate on their own, sometimes looking to external avenues of aid might provide businesses with just the bump they need. In this case, <a href=\"http://www.sba.gov/community/blogs/community-blogs/small-business-matters/small-business-guide-exporting-part-1-getting\" target=\"_blank\">the U.S. Small Business Administration</a> (SBA) is actually a strong partner for entrepreneurs to vet when considering small-business exporting.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.huffingtonpost.com/karen-mills/small-business-exporting_b_2814446.html\" target=\"_blank\">In a recent editorial piece</a>, outgoing SBA Administrator Karen Mills detailed the lengths the agency goes to help small businesses prepare and fund exporting operations. Mills said since fiscal year 2009, the SBA has guaranteed some 6,400 loans to entrepreneurial exporters worth more than $3.3 billion supporting $6.3 billion exports. She also noted the agency employs 19 international trade experts at assistance centers and have trained more than 58,000 small businesses in exporting strategies and financing options.</p><p>Registering with <a href=\"http://export.gov/begin/index.asp\" target=\"_blank\">Export.gov</a> can also give small-business owners access to key resources like trade agreements and market research.</p><h2><strong>Where In The World <span style=\"text-decoration: line-through\">Is Carmen Sandiego</span> Should You Export To</strong></h2><p>Exporting can be as simple as selling to our neighbors to the north and south – Canada and Mexico – or entail a more expansive operation that requires overseas management.</p><p>But before the concept of a globalized small business and the myriad choices owners are pressed with when deciding where to export causes you alarm, consider the story of Orly International, a California-based business that makes nail care products. <a href=\"http://articles.latimes.com/2011/feb/21/business/la-fi-smallbiz-export-20110221\" target=\"_blank\">As profiled in The Los Angeles Times</a>, Orly’s foreign sales growth outstripped that of their annual domestic increases. And they’re doing it by selling all over: The Times reported the 105-employee firm exports to 82 countries.</p><p>“We just have seen such a growth opportunity in our export business that we have accelerated that emphasis to build more export markets,” said Bob Hobe, Orly’s vice president for international business development, told the newspaper.</p><p>To start, it’s well worth investigating your prospects in emerging economies – primarily, Brazil, China and India. Together, the population of the three developing economies total some 2.7 million, a sizeable consumer base. These countries are rapidly ascending the economic chain after lying dormant for some time. As such, they are prime areas of expansion for small-business owners with exporting in mind.</p><p>Another route of exporting to consider is selling to old standbys, like Western European markets, and countries on good terms with the United States that have shown a proclivity for buying American-made products. Countries like Australia, the Philippines, South Africa and Japan all come to mind.</p><p>Besides the big three of Brazil, China and India, also keep an eye on other emerging markets that boast a growing middle class and increasing demand for consumer products. Like Latin America countries including Chile and Argentina.</p><h2><strong>Set Up Digital Shop</strong></h2><p>One way entrepreneurs can take exporting duties into their own hands is by creating an<a href=\"http://income.com/1159/tap-into-billions-4-ways-to-strike-gold-with-foreign-ecommerce/\" target=\"_blank\">ecommerce site specifically geared toward foreign customers</a>. You don’t need to round the Cape Horn anymore to talk to the other side of the Pacific, just hop online. Ecommerce facilitates simplified business-consumer relationships and transaction and allows you to reach an ever-expanding global market from your office chair.</p><p><a href=\"http://income.com/how-to-build-a-website-a-step-by-step-tutorial/\" target=\"_blank\">Online opportunities</a> abound and entrepreneurs need to take advantage of their technological capabilities to compete on a global stage. <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/small-business-network/2013/feb/18/online-sales-overseas\" target=\"_blank\">A survey by Freelancer.co.uk</a> or 2,200 small business in the United Kingdom found a year-over-year increase of 36 percent in the number of firms selling products overseas via ecommerce. It also found a 32 percent increase in startups that sell products exclusively online.</p><p><a href=\"http://income.com/\">Income.com</a> wants entrepreneurs to understand the money-making opportunities available to them outside the United States. In order to tap global markets, you might need some help from government programs, but in the end, it’s up to you. Decide which emerging economy to focus on and be sure to have an ecommerce-ready site for easy exporting.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><a href=\"http://income.com/forum/forum.php\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" title=\"ebook-banner\" alt=\" \" src=\"http://income.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/Community_banner.png\" width=\"468\" height=\"60\" /></a></p><p style=\"text-align: center\"><a href=\"http://www.mylanderpages.com/income/howtocreateawebsiteebook_4\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-577\" title=\"ebook-banner\" alt=\" \" src=\"http://income.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/howtocreateawebsiteebook1.png\" width=\"641\" height=\"123\" /></a></p><p>The post <a href=\"http://income.com/1934/grow-your-small-business-by-exporting/\">Grow Your Small Business By Exporting</a> appeared first on <a href=\"http://income.com\">income.com</a>.</p><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/income/YOKa/~4/pdViAvltCp0\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\"/>" "http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/income/YOKa/~3/pdViAvltCp0/" (20809 49503) new 3 nil nil ((title nil "Grow Your Small Business By Exporting") (link nil "http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/income/YOKa/~3/pdViAvltCp0/") (comments nil "http://income.com/1934/grow-your-small-business-by-exporting/#comments") (pubDate nil "Wed, 20 Mar 2013 14:02:07 +0000") (dc:creator nil "Tedd Johnson") (category nil "Articles") (category nil "Entrepreneur Advice") (category nil "Small Business") (guid ((isPermaLink . "false")) "http://income.com/?p=1934") (description nil "<p>U.S. entrepreneurs benefit immensely from residing in one of the most populous consumer markets: 300 million people is a big number. But so too is the some 6.7 billion other individuals that constitute the world&#8217;s population outside of the states. Want some small-business tips for success? All those people are consumers in their own right, [...]</p><p>The post <a href=\"http://income.com/1934/grow-your-small-business-by-exporting/\">Grow Your Small Business By Exporting</a> appeared first on <a href=\"http://income.com\">income.com</a>.</p>") (content:encoded nil "<div id=\"attachment_1935\" class=\"wp-caption alignleft\" style=\"width: 310px\"><a href=\"http://income.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/x_0_0_0_14084634_300.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-1935\" alt=\"Ecommerce helps facilitate small-business exporting.  \" src=\"http://income.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/x_0_0_0_14084634_300.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"220\" /></a><p class=\"wp-caption-text\">Ecommerce helps facilitate small-business exporting.</p></div><p>U.S. entrepreneurs benefit immensely from residing in one of the most populous consumer markets: 300 million people is a big number.</p><p>But so too is the some 6.7 billion other individuals that constitute the world&#8217;s population outside of the states.</p><p>Want some small-business tips for success? All those people are consumers in their own right, too. If you are serious about making your small business all it can be, you need to investigate exporting if you want to tap the growing global market and establish your startup as a true force to be reckoned with.</p><p>However, <a href=\"http://income.com/\">Income.com</a> understands that many entrepreneurs, while still in tune with a global perspective, don&#8217;t have much knowledge on the subject of exports, how the logistics work out and which foreign markets are the best. In order to prime your business for exporting, it may help to consider federal assistance and do a little homework on where your products would sell the best.</p><h2><strong>SBA Can Help</strong></h2><p>While it&#8217;s quite clear entrepreneurs like to operate on their own, sometimes looking to external avenues of aid might provide businesses with just the bump they need. In this case, <a href=\"http://www.sba.gov/community/blogs/community-blogs/small-business-matters/small-business-guide-exporting-part-1-getting\" target=\"_blank\">the U.S. Small Business Administration</a> (SBA) is actually a strong partner for entrepreneurs to vet when considering small-business exporting.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.huffingtonpost.com/karen-mills/small-business-exporting_b_2814446.html\" target=\"_blank\">In a recent editorial piece</a>, outgoing SBA Administrator Karen Mills detailed the lengths the agency goes to help small businesses prepare and fund exporting operations. Mills said since fiscal year 2009, the SBA has guaranteed some 6,400 loans to entrepreneurial exporters worth more than $3.3 billion supporting $6.3 billion exports. She also noted the agency employs 19 international trade experts at assistance centers and have trained more than 58,000 small businesses in exporting strategies and financing options.</p><p>Registering with <a href=\"http://export.gov/begin/ind