od to market to sporting dog owners or an all-around healthy entree to keep cats lean and mean &#8211; emphasis on the latter &#8211; there are a number of different products to create. Packaging is also a crucial element. People eat foods that look good, and before that, they choose foods with the most aesthetically pleasing packaging. There&#8217;s ample opportunity to create color-popping labels that attract attention, and ultimately, business.</p><h2><strong>All Dogs Go To Heaven</strong></h2><p>Unfortunately, like all things we love, cherish and share memories of, we meet a harsh reality when pets die. But there&#8217;s a better way to burying the dead in a mass grave and encountering a Pet Semetary-like experience.</p><p>Cremating pets is a trending business venture and operators are finding that pet owners are willing to pay top money for services.</p><p>&#8220;When people come to the funeral home and I tell them how much it is to cremate their grandfather, it&#8217;s never cheap enough for them,&#8221; Bob Walczyk, owner of a Green Bay pet crematorium, <a href=\"http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2012-09-07/theres-never-been-a-better-time-to-be-a-dead-pet#p1\" target=\"_blank\">told Bloomberg Businessweek</a>. &#8220;They&#8217;ll say, &#8216;How much? You&#8217;ve got to be kidding me!&#8217; But when the exact same family brings their dog next door, they don&#8217;t even ask about money. They just tell me what they want and they take out their checkbook.&#8221;</p><p>There&#8217;s also an opportunity to resonate on an emotional level with patrons. You can repurpose ashes into a ceramic decoration of sorts that includes an imprint of the pet&#8217;s paw that owners will certainly appreciate as a memento.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.income.com/\">Income.com</a> knows brainstorming ideas for starting a small business can be difficult, but sometimes you need look no farther than the ball of fur cuddled around your ankles. Owners are increasingly spending big money for pet products and services, and you can make money from that by starting up a business that caters to such needs. Be it obedience training, food preparation or crematory services, pet small businesses are worth investigating.</p><p><a href=\"http://income.com/forum/forum.php\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" title=\"ebook-banner\" alt=\" \" src=\"http://income.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/Community_banner.png\" width=\"468\" height=\"60\" /></a></p><p style=\"text-align: center\"><a href=\"http://www.mylanderpages.com/income/howtocreateawebsiteebook_4\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-577\" title=\"ebook-banner\" alt=\" \" src=\"http://income.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/howtocreateawebsiteebook1.png\" width=\"641\" height=\"123\" /></a></p><p>The post <a href=\"http://income.com/1928/3-ideas-for-starting-a-small-business-in-the-pet-niche/\">3 Ideas For Starting A Small Business In The Pet Niche</a> appeared first on <a href=\"http://income.com\">income.com</a>.</p><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/income/YOKa/~4/oGljsEcFe_Q\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\"/>") (wfw:commentRss nil "http://income.com/1928/3-ideas-for-starting-a-small-business-in-the-pet-niche/feed/") (slash:comments nil "0") (feedburner:origLink nil "http://income.com/1928/3-ideas-for-starting-a-small-business-in-the-pet-niche/"))) ("Small-Business Marketing Help: Are Daily Deals Worth It?" "<div id=\"attachment_1925\" class=\"wp-caption alignleft\" style=\"width: 310px\"><a href=\"http://income.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/x_0_0_0_14084166_300.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-1925\" alt=\"Daily deal sites like Groupon are a crap shoot, but coupon marketing in general can still be effective.\" src=\"http://income.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/x_0_0_0_14084166_300.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a><p class=\"wp-caption-text\">Daily deal sites like Groupon are a crap shoot, but coupon marketing in general can still be effective.</p></div><p>It wasn’t too long ago that small business hailed the onset of the daily deal as a lifesaver for attracting customers.</p><p>My, how quickly things change.</p><p>Now, entrepreneurs are starting to avoid daily deals sites like they’re the plague. And for good reason; daily coupons aren’t actually all they’re cracked up to be in terms of benefits to the small business. To add to that, the constant state of flux leading companies like Groupon and LivingSocial find themselves in have scared off many.</p><p><a href=\"http://income.com/\">Income.com</a> warns you to not depend too much on getting small-business marketing help from daily deals. Instead, if you plan on offering customers limited coupons <a href=\"http://income.com/1128/two-cheap-tricks-to-have-your-customers-begging-for-more/\" target=\"_blank\">in order to boost loyalty</a>and business, you’ll need to investigate some alternative options, including making your own incentivized coupons and working with a provider who’s more attune to small-business needs.</p><h2><strong>What’s the difference between Groupon and a sinking ship?</strong></h2><p>Trick question: There is none.</p><p>The latest news about Groupon broke when the company announced it had fired its founder and CEO Andrew Mason. The move was enough to drive up Groupon’s much-maligned stock shares, but it did little to quell simmering fears and trepidations small-business owners have. Groupon was already floundering in the face of enormous expectations and a change at the top <a href=\"http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2013-02-28/firing-andrew-mason-wont-save-groupon#r=hpt-ls\" target=\"_blank\">still isn’t the fix entrepreneurs were looking for</a>.</p><p>Already, small-business owners have abandoned the marketing medium they had flocked to not long before. <a href=\"http://www.manta.com/media/holiday_survey_10302012\" target=\"_blank\">A Manata survey</a> from late last year found 82 percent of surveyed entrepreneurs didn’t run a daily deal or opted not to during the buildup to the 2012 holiday shopping season.</p><p>Their main grievances with the daily deal formula? One, small businesses have to pay a fee on top of an already significantly marked-down product or service; and two, the deals did very little to inspire repeat business. In fact, 11 percent of those who ran deals said they lost money or got no boost.</p><p>Groupon’s main competitor in the daily deal arena hasn’t fared much better, LivingSocial <a href=\"http://www.bizjournals.com/washington/blog/techflash/2013/02/livingsocial-cancels-bonuses-amid.html\" target=\"_blank\">lost $650 million in 2012</a> and continues to tank on financial goals, forcing the company to cancel all performance bonuses.</p><p>So what’s a small-business owner to do when he or she looks to utilize coupon marketing? Well, the strategies to avoid are obvious, but the ones to try out are less clear, requiring entrepreneurs to put some real thought into how they use coupons for small-business marketing help.</p><h2><strong>Encourage customer loyalty</strong></h2><p>While in theory coupons are huge generators of repeat customers, Groupon’s daily deals did little to inspire loyalty among users. The root of the problem? Loyal customers didn’t browse and use coupons to the same degree as deal hunters who were in the market for a one-off purchase where they could save as much as possible.</p><p>In order to counter that approach, you’ll need to make and distribute coupons that clearly demonstrate to customers that they can enjoy savings by giving their continued business to a firm.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.smallbusinessnewz.com/effective-coupons-and-repeat-business-2008-06\" target=\"_blank\">Take for instance Chris Crum’s experience</a>. Writing for Small Business Newz, Crum said he had some trouble with his brakes and went to a mechanic. After getting the problem fixed, the mechanic gave him a coupon for 20 percent off the next service. When he had more trouble with his car, he knew where to take it.</p><p>Taking the one-off approach with a daily deal aggregator might lead to a singular boom in business, but it won’t prove to be a viable strategy for attracting consumers and converting them into long-time customers.</p><h2><strong>Is a Groupon of another name still Groupon?</strong></h2><p>In short, yes and no.</p><p>While <a href=\"http://getprivy.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Privy</a> is a deal site that works similar to Groupon – small-business owners have to go through an outside entity to distribute the deal - Privy works in a way that is more beneficial to small businesses.</p><p>For instance, while Groupon and similar deal aggregators can take up to 50 percent off in transaction fees, Privy only levies a 15 percent fee, founder Benjamin Jabbawy <a href=\"http://www.biztechmagazine.com/article/2012/04/privy-daily-deals-alternative-businesses-control\" target=\"_blank\">told BizTech magazine</a>.</p><p>Privy works by having small-business owners customize their own deal, either a loyalty promotion or an acquisition initiative, which Privy then distributes through email and a variety of<a href=\"http://income.com/90/social-media-a-proven-marketing-initiative-for-entrepreneurs/\" target=\"_blank\">social media channels</a>. This allows you to collect addresses of coupon redeemers and keep tabs on how the campaign fared.</p><p>“Privy flips the model and puts the business in the driver’s seat,” the BizTech article reads. “It lets businesses offer daily deals on their <a href=\"http://income.com/how-to-build-a-website-a-step-by-step-tutorial/\" target=\"_blank\">websites</a> or Facebook page at their own price and pace. Business owners set the terms of how much of a discount the deal will offer, how long it will last, and how it can be redeemed.”</p><p><a href=\"http://income.com/\">Income.com</a> wants entrepreneurs to know coupon marketing as a whole is not dead, but the daily deal model sure is. You’re better off ditching Groupon and LivingSocial while you can and instead focusing on your own coupons or working with a startup specifically catering to small businesses’ coupon needs. Just remember, fostering customer loyalty should be the main objective and large-scale aggregators do little to inspire such confidence in businesses and consumers alike.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><a href=\"http://income.com/forum/forum.php\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" title=\"ebook-banner\" alt=\" \" src=\"http://income.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/Community_banner.png\" width=\"468\" height=\"60\" /></a></p><p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://www.mylanderpages.com/income/howtocreateawebsiteebook_4\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-577\" title=\"ebook-banner\" alt=\" \" src=\"http://income.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/howtocreateawebsiteebook1.png\" width=\"641\" height=\"123\" /></a></p><p>The post <a href=\"http://income.com/1924/small-business-marketing-help-are-daily-deals-worth-it/\">Small-Business Marketing Help: Are Daily Deals Worth It?</a> appeared first on <a href=\"http://income.com\">income.com</a>.</p><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/income/YOKa/~4/iQ-2tGVP4RM\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\"/>" "http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/income/YOKa/~3/iQ-2tGVP4RM/" (20807 16436) new 5 nil nil ((title nil "Small-Business Marketing Help: Are Daily Deals Worth It?") (link nil "http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/income/YOKa/~3/iQ-2tGVP4RM/") (comments nil "http://income.com/1924/small-business-marketing-help-are-daily-deals-worth-it/#comments") (pubDate nil "Mon, 18 Mar 2013 16:26:28 +0000") (dc:creator nil "Tedd Johnson") (category nil "Articles") (category nil "Small Business") (category nil "Small Business Marketing Strategies") (guid ((isPermaLink . "false")) "http://income.com/?p=1924") (description nil "<p>It wasn&#8217;t too long ago that small business hailed the onset of the daily deal as a lifesaver for attracting customers. My, how quickly things change. Now, entrepreneurs are starting to avoid daily deals sites 