ore attune to small-business needs.</p><h2><strong>What&#8217;s the difference between Groupon and a sinking ship?</strong></h2><p>Trick question: There is none.</p><p>The latest news about Groupon broke when the company announced it had fired its founder and CEO Andrew Mason. The move was enough to drive up Groupon&#8217;s much-maligned stock shares, but it did little to quell simmering fears and trepidations small-business owners have. Groupon was already floundering in the face of enormous expectations and a change at the top <a href=\"http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2013-02-28/firing-andrew-mason-wont-save-groupon#r=hpt-ls\" target=\"_blank\">still isn&#8217;t the fix entrepreneurs were looking for</a>.</p><p>Already, small-business owners have abandoned the marketing medium they had flocked to not long before. <a href=\"http://www.manta.com/media/holiday_survey_10302012\" target=\"_blank\">A Manata survey</a> from late last year found 82 percent of surveyed entrepreneurs didn&#8217;t run a daily deal or opted not to during the buildup to the 2012 holiday shopping season.</p><p>Their main grievances with the daily deal formula? One, small businesses have to pay a fee on top of an already significantly marked-down product or service; and two, the deals did very little to inspire repeat business. In fact, 11 percent of those who ran deals said they lost money or got no boost.</p><p>Groupon&#8217;s main competitor in the daily deal arena hasn&#8217;t fared much better, LivingSocial <a href=\"http://www.bizjournals.com/washington/blog/techflash/2013/02/livingsocial-cancels-bonuses-amid.html\" target=\"_blank\">lost $650 million in 2012</a> and continues to tank on financial goals, forcing the company to cancel all performance bonuses.</p><p>So what&#8217;s a small-business owner to do when he or she looks to utilize coupon marketing? Well, the strategies to avoid are obvious, but the ones to try out are less clear, requiring entrepreneurs to put some real thought into how they use coupons for small-business marketing help.</p><h2><strong>Encourage customer loyalty</strong></h2><p>While in theory coupons are huge generators of repeat customers, Groupon&#8217;s daily deals did little to inspire loyalty among users. The root of the problem? Loyal customers didn&#8217;t browse and use coupons to the same degree as deal hunters who were in the market for a one-off purchase where they could save as much as possible.</p><p>In order to counter that approach, you&#8217;ll need to make and distribute coupons that clearly demonstrate to customers that they can enjoy savings by giving their continued business to a firm.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.smallbusinessnewz.com/effective-coupons-and-repeat-business-2008-06\" target=\"_blank\">Take for instance Chris Crum&#8217;s experience</a>. Writing for Small Business Newz, Crum said he had some trouble with his brakes and went to a mechanic. After getting the problem fixed, the mechanic gave him a coupon for 20 percent off the next service. When he had more trouble with his car, he knew where to take it.</p><p>Taking the one-off approach with a daily deal aggregator might lead to a singular boom in business, but it won&#8217;t prove to be a viable strategy for attracting consumers and converting them into long-time customers.</p><h2><strong>Is a Groupon of another name still Groupon?</strong></h2><p>In short, yes and no.</p><p>While <a href=\"http://getprivy.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Privy</a> is a deal site that works similar to Groupon &#8211; small-business owners have to go through an outside entity to distribute the deal - Privy works in a way that is more beneficial to small businesses.</p><p>For instance, while Groupon and similar deal aggregators can take up to 50 percent off in transaction fees, Privy only levies a 15 percent fee, founder Benjamin Jabbawy <a href=\"http://www.biztechmagazine.com/article/2012/04/privy-daily-deals-alternative-businesses-control\" target=\"_blank\">told BizTech magazine</a>.</p><p>Privy works by having small-business owners customize their own deal, either a loyalty promotion or an acquisition initiative, which Privy then distributes through email and a variety of<a href=\"http://income.com/90/social-media-a-proven-marketing-initiative-for-entrepreneurs/\" target=\"_blank\">social media channels</a>. This allows you to collect addresses of coupon redeemers and keep tabs on how the campaign fared.</p><p>&#8220;Privy flips the model and puts the business in the driver&#8217;s seat,&#8221; the BizTech article reads. &#8220;It lets businesses offer daily deals on their <a href=\"http://income.com/how-to-build-a-website-a-step-by-step-tutorial/\" target=\"_blank\">websites</a> or Facebook page at their own price and pace. Business owners set the terms of how much of a discount the deal will offer, how long it will last, and how it can be redeemed.&#8221;</p><p><a href=\"http://income.com/\">Income.com</a> wants entrepreneurs to know coupon marketing as a whole is not dead, but the daily deal model sure is. You&#8217;re better off ditching Groupon and LivingSocial while you can and instead focusing on your own coupons or working with a startup specifically catering to small businesses&#8217; coupon needs. Just remember, fostering customer loyalty should be the main objective and large-scale aggregators do little to inspire such confidence in businesses and consumers alike.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><a href=\"http://income.com/forum/forum.php\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" title=\"ebook-banner\" alt=\" \" src=\"http://income.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/Community_banner.png\" width=\"468\" height=\"60\" /></a></p><p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://www.mylanderpages.com/income/howtocreateawebsiteebook_4\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-577\" title=\"ebook-banner\" alt=\" \" src=\"http://income.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/howtocreateawebsiteebook1.png\" width=\"641\" height=\"123\" /></a></p><p>The post <a href=\"http://income.com/1924/small-business-marketing-help-are-daily-deals-worth-it/\">Small-Business Marketing Help: Are Daily Deals Worth It?</a> appeared first on <a href=\"http://income.com\">income.com</a>.</p><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/income/YOKa/~4/iQ-2tGVP4RM\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\"/>") (wfw:commentRss nil "http://income.com/1924/small-business-marketing-help-are-daily-deals-worth-it/feed/") (slash:comments nil "0") (feedburner:origLink nil "http://income.com/1924/small-business-marketing-help-are-daily-deals-worth-it/"))) ("Real Ways to Make Money Online from Odds and Ends" "<div id=\"attachment_1902\" class=\"wp-caption alignleft\" style=\"width: 448px\"><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/aigle_dore/5238601894/\"><img class=\" wp-image-1902  \" alt=\"Copyright by Moyan Brenn\" src=\"http://income.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/Screen-Shot-2013-03-04-at-4.22.17-PM.png\" width=\"438\" height=\"294\" /></a><p class=\"wp-caption-text\">Copyright by Moyan Brenn</p></div><p>Every entrepreneur knows <a href=\"http://income.com/how-to-build-a-website-a-step-by-step-tutorial/\" target=\"_blank\">online small businesses</a> are golden opportunities for profiting off the influx of money flowing through digital channels.</p><p>There are real ways to make money online – recent research from eMarketer found global ecommerce sales <a href=\"http://www.emarketer.com/Article/Ecommerce-Sales-Topped-1-Trillion-First-Time-2012/1009649\" target=\"_blank\">topped $1 trillion for the first time ever in 2012</a>, with $343 billion occurring in the United States alone – but not all of them might have to be central to your small business.</p><p>Sure, getting online is the most important thing an entrepreneur can do to grow his or her small business into a money-making machine, but the internet is a vast place with nearly unlimited opportunities for you to make money off almost anything you do.</p><p><a href=\"http://income.com/\">Income.com</a> wants you to know if you’ve got a hobby, chances are, you can capitalize on it online.</p><p>Whether you make arts and crafts knick-knacks, have an affinity for emerging technologies or you think you’ve got the next great American novel, there are <a href=\"http://www.foxnews.com/tech/2013/01/05/6-great-ways-to-make-money-online/\" target=\"_blank\">real ways to make money online from odd jobs</a> that can net you a big digital payday.</p><h2><strong>Lab rats wanted</strong></h2><p>Apps are all the rage nowadays. We have apps to start our cars, dim the lights at home while we’re away and even translator apps that you can speak directly into and hear fluent Italian come out of.</p><p>That’s some pretty sophisticated technology, so how does it make its way to the market with full confidence from the publisher? By getting tested by real-life users.</p><p>So, if you’re a tech-geek and you’ve got some downtime to try out some up-and-coming apps, you might as well earn some money while doing so.</p><p>How, you ask? <a href=\"http://www.wahadventures.com/2011/08/utest-com-earn-money-testing-software.html\" target=\"_blank\">By signing up on uTest</a>, the world’s largest software testing community with more than 70,000 testers spread across 190 countries. By signing up with uTest, you can become a paid tester for mobile and desktops apps. After filling out your profile, uTest will send out test invites matched to your profile and you’ll get to trial software to find bugs. Testers are paid twice a month for approved reports the file.</p><h2><strong>Snapshots pay off</strong></h2><p>In the age of Instagram, everyone fashions themselves to be a master photographer. Take a picture of a sidewalk crack, throw in a sepia filter for good measure and voilà – Louis Daguerre who?</p><p>Turns out, you actually can be a professional photographer and get paid for all the quick pics you take in a day even if it’s not your actual business. Stock photo databases like Thinkstock, iStockphoto, Shutterstock and Dreamstime are always in the market to build their ever-increasing caches of animals in doctor coats and businesspeople on computers.</p><p>But believe it or not, it’s a lucrative business; Yuri Arcurs, the <a href=\"http://arcurs.com/\" target=\"_blank\">self-proclaimed world’s top-selling stock photographer</a>, sells a picture every eight seconds! Stock photos get a hilarious reputation for being outlandish or flat out bad, but the fact is databases will pay for your photos, and more often than not, someone will find a use for them.</p><h2><strong>Arts and crafts time for adults</strong></h2><p>If you’ve got some artistic flair or <a href=\"http://income.com/1623/how-my-kid-brother-turned-passion-into-profit/\" target=\"_blank\">just have a passion</a> for being creative, you’ll never have to rue the day you pursued a major in art history again if you get online and start selling on the internet.</p><p>If you make jewelry, design home decorations, knit sweaters or even make specialty tags for dog collars, you better take advantage of the opportunities afforded to you by ecommerce marketplaces like Etsy, which has developed a massive following and carved out a niche space online for its vintage and homemade product sellers and buyers. ArtFire is another great online shopping hub for artisans to peddle their wares.</p><p>Such ecommerce sites are a better bet than large-scale marketplaces like eBay or Amazon for some entrepreneurs, as they can attract a more dedicated following and benefit from a specialized atmosphere that allows you to market your products the way you want to.</p><h2><strong>Typewriters are dead. Long live typing writers!</strong></h2><p>Being an author has historically been an underpaid and underappreciated profession, but the culture of e-books has revolutionized the way underground writers can make money off online books.</p><p>The rapid proliferation of reading devices like Amazon’s Kindle and the iPad have enabled consumers to gather their own digital libraries, and they’re gobbling up all the e-books they can. You won’t need a 1,000-page masterpiece to become an accomplished author in contemporary literature. Fantasy novels have caught like wildfire, thanks to George R.R. Martin’s Game of Thrones, and romance novels have found new life in the online arena, driven in part by the Fifty Shades of Grey trilogy, which is routinely a top-seller online.</p><p><a href=\"http://income.com/\">Income.com</a> wants to remind entrepreneurs that <a href=\"http://income.com/67/3-keys-for-starting-a-successful-small-business/\" target=\"_blank\">real ways to make money online</a> don’t just begin and end with small-business websites. If you’ve got something you’re good at, you can profit from it by taking your talents to south beach online. Test software, write a book, take a photo or knit some kitten mittens; whatever you do, you can make money online if you find the right channel.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><a href=\"http://income.com/forum/forum.php\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" title=\"ebook-banner\" alt=\" \" src=\"http://income.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/Community_banner.png\" width=\"468\" height=\"60\" /></a></p><p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://www.mylanderpages.com/income/howtocreateawebsiteebook_4\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-577\" title=\"ebook-banner\" alt=\" \" src=\"http://income.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/howtocreateawebsiteebook1.png\" width=\"641\" height=\"123\" /></a></p><p>The post <a href=\"http://income.com/1901/real-ways-to-make-money-online-from-odds-and-ends/\">Real Ways to Make Money Online from Odds and Ends</a> appeared first on <a href=\"http://income.com\">income.com</a>.</p><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/income/YOKa/~4/lsE5QpLI5i0\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\"/>" "http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/income/YOKa/~3/lsE5QpLI5i0/" (20799 13927) new 6 nil nil ((title nil "Real Ways to Make Money Online from Odds and Ends") (link nil "http: